{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/pancreatitis-chronic/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"bfa52d50-3b9c-54bf-b86b-a6ec4d6efd15","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 210d89bf-7012-484c-97a4-d00f799bb673 --><h1>Pancreatitis - chronic: Summary</h1><!-- end field 210d89bf-7012-484c-97a4-d00f799bb673 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 5ca6473a-d5ef-48f6-a368-3d7c520d558d --><!-- begin field 8921a92b-de13-4556-9dbb-1c320b9751d2 --><ul><li>Chronic pancreatitis is a chronic, irreversible, inflammation and/or fibrosis of the pancreas, often characterized by severe pain and progressive endocrine and exocrine insufficiency. </li><li>Chronic pancreatitis is commonly caused by alcohol misuse or is idiopathic. Other rarer causes include autoimmune or metabolic disorders, genetic abnormalities, and drugs such as thiazide diuretics, azathioprine, tetracyclines, and cimetidine.</li><li>Complications of chronic pancreatitis include:<ul><li>Chronic pain.</li><li>Endocrine insufficiency with failure to produce insulin, causing impaired glucose regulation and diabetes mellitus.</li><li>Exocrine insufficiency with failure to produce digestive enzymes, causing maldigestion and malabsorption.</li><li>Pancreatic calcification.</li><li>Pseudocyst formation.</li></ul></li><li>Chronic pancreatitis should be suspected if a person presents with chronic or recurrent upper or generalized abdominal pain, particularly if they have a history or clinical features of alcohol misuse. Pain may radiate to the back, and may be relieved by sitting up and leaning forward.</li><li>Other clinical features of chronic pancreatitis include:</li><ul><li>Nausea and vomiting, bloating, weight loss, or steatorrhoea.<br></li><li>Jaundice and signs of chronic liver disease.<br></li></ul><li>Early diagnosis of chronic pancreatitis is usually difficult and requires referral for investigation in secondary care.</li><ul><li>Urgent admission should be arranged if the person presents with an episode of acute pancreatitis. For further information, see the CKS topic on Pancreatitis - acute.</li><li>Refer urgently, depending on clinical judgement, if a person presents with a complication of suspected chronic pancreatitis.</li><li>If urgent referral or admission is not indicated, investigations such as abdominal ultrasonography and blood tests may be helpful. <br></li></ul><li>A person with confirmed chronic pancreatitis should be managed by a specialist team in secondary care, but primary care may have a role in the following:</li><ul><li>Provision of alcohol and smoking cessation advice.<br></li><li>Provision of adequate pain relief.<br></li><li>Screening for diabetes mellitus.<br></li><li>Continuing treatment initiated in secondary care, such as pancreatic enzyme supplementation for steatorrhoea or poor nutritional status, or corticosteroids for the treatment of autoimmune chronic pancreatitis.</li></ul><li>Referral should be considered if appropriate, such as to a:<ul><li>Gastroenterology or pancreatic specialist on the 2-week wait cancer pathway if the person has unexplained progressive weight loss.</li><li>Gastroenterology, pancreatico-biliary surgery, a pancreatic centre, or pain clinic team if the person has uncontrolled pain, or recurrent attacks of acute on chronic pancreatitis.</li><li>Diabetes specialist if the person develops diabetes.</li><li>Dietitian for advice regarding a low-fat, high-protein, high-calorie diet with fat-soluble vitamin supplementation.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 8921a92b-de13-4556-9dbb-1c320b9751d2 --><!-- end item 5ca6473a-d5ef-48f6-a368-3d7c520d558d -->","topic":{"id":"d3bdd09e-867d-5b95-ba2d-6665c70e40a5","topicId":"d9dbbfb6-e615-4d8a-8af3-3c73ae8f1e4e","topicName":"Pancreatitis - chronic","slug":"pancreatitis-chronic","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"bfa52d50-3b9c-54bf-b86b-a6ec4d6efd15","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Su